        <section>
            <h2>What Other Cryptocurrencies Can You Use Besides Bitcoin?</h2>
            <p>Crypto betting sites usually support a selection of altcoins in addition to Bitcoin, which you can use to deposit and withdraw funds from your betting account.</p>

            <h3>Ethereum (ETH)</h3>
            <p>Only second to BTC in value, Ethereum is a popular coin offered at crypto sports betting sites. Combining smart contracts with lightning-fast processing, ETH is ideal if you're looking to bet small, but keep in mind it has higher mining fees than Bitcoin.</p>

            <h3>Dogecoin (DOGE)</h3>
            <p>Launched as the first doggy coin and the first meme coin, DOGE was initially created to poke fun at Bitcoin. To its creators' surprise, the coin began gaining value and is now a popular option at crypto bookies thanks to its fast processing capabilities.</p>

            <h3>Litecoin (LTC)</h3>
            <p>Built using a modified BTC codebase, Litecoin is a favourite among bettors for its reliability and quick transactions. Many cryptocurrency betting platforms offer high-value LTC withdrawals.</p>

            <h3>Bitcoin Cash (BCH)</h3>
            <p>A spin-off of Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash makes it easy to send money 24/7 to anywhere in the world, including your crypto betting account. Despite mining difficulties and slightly slower transaction confirmations, BCH remains a popular coin at crypto bookies.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>How Do You Start Betting with Cryptocurrency?</h2>
            <p>When it comes to Bitcoin betting sites, the process of placing a bet is much the same as it is at traditional sports betting sites. However, when making a deposit or a withdrawal, things are quite different.</p>

            <h3>How to Deposit with Bitcoin at a Crypto Sportsbook</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Visit a crypto exchange (Coinbase, for example) and register a profile to set up your crypto wallet.</li>
                <li>Browse the cryptocurrencies available and purchase crypto to the value of your choosing using your debit or credit card.</li>
                <li>Once your cryptocurrency is available in your wallet, launch your crypto sportsbook and register an account.</li>
                <li>Open the bookie's "Banking" page and select the crypto you want to use.</li>
                <li>Fill in how much you're going to deposit using this method and confirm.</li>
                <li>Copy the sportsbook's crypto address and paste it into your crypto wallet.</li>
                <li>Confirm the deposit amount on your crypto wallet and approve the transaction.</li>
                <li>Your funds should be accessible in your betting account in just a few minutes.</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>How to Withdraw</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Make sure you're signed into your crypto sports betting account.</li>
                <li>Launch the "Banking" page and make sure you're on the "Withdrawals" tab.</li>
                <li>Select the crypto you want to use for your withdrawal and fill in how much you want to withdraw.</li>
                <li>Paste your crypto wallet address into the block provided.</li>
                <li>Check that all the details are correct, and confirm the transaction.</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="pro-tip">
                <strong>Pro Tip:</strong>
                Always double-check wallet addresses before confirming transactions. Crypto transactions are irreversible, and sending to the wrong address means permanent loss of funds.
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>How Can You Bet Responsibly with Cryptocurrency?</h2>
            <p>Privacy and security are two top features of Bitcoin betting sites, but ultimately, your online safety still rests with you. There are several things you should and shouldn't do if you want to stay safe when betting at crypto sites.</p>

            <div class="responsible-list do-list">
                <h4>Do:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Use a Trusted Crypto Wallet</strong> – Pick a wallet that has a good reputation. You can check out user reviews on forums to find top options. Also, rather store funds in your crypto wallet rather than in your betting account.</li>
                    <li><strong>Stick to Coins You Know</strong> – There are regularly new altcoins entering the market, many which are touted by influencers. However, these are highly volatile and carry great risk, making it safer to stick to coins like Bitcoin and Ethereum which are trustworthy.</li>
                    <li><strong>Set Up 2-FA or Biometric Sign-in</strong> – Unfortunately, there is always a chance of online fraud. This makes it essential to set up two-factor authentication or biometric sign-in on your betting account, which makes it challenging for hackers to access your information.</li>
                    <li><strong>Gamble Responsibly</strong> – Practice responsible gambling by staying within your means. Setting a budget, applying limits to your betting account, or reaching out to problem gambling resources are the best ways to stay safe.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="responsible-list dont-list">
                <h4>Don't:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Use Public WiFi</strong> – Hackers often broadcast WiFi networks that imitate public WiFi networks. If you accidentally join one of these false networks, any details or login information you share while using that network become available to the hacker.</li>
                    <li><strong>Share Your Wallet Address with Just Anyone</strong> – While sharing your wallet address is relatively safe, sharing your private keys or other key details about your crypto wallet can leave you vulnerable to hackers.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="pro-tip">
                <strong>Pro Tip:</strong>
                Rather set up a WiFi hotspot from your mobile device if you want to use the internet in a public area. This requires you to input a specific password, which is much safer.
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="faq-section">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>Is Crypto Betting Legal in the UK?</h3>
                <p>Yes, crypto betting is legal in the UK when conducted through properly licensed operators. The UK Gambling Commission doesn't distinguish between payment methods—if the betting site holds a valid license, you can legally use cryptocurrency to bet.</p>
                <p>The legality concerns the operator's licensing status, not your payment method. Sites licensed by the UK Gambling Commission, Malta Gaming Authority, or Gibraltar Gambling Commission operate legally for UK residents regardless of whether you pay with pounds, euros, or Bitcoin.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>What Happens if Bitcoin's Price Changes While I'm Betting?</h3>
                <p>Most crypto betting sites convert your cryptocurrency to pounds, euros, or USD at the moment of deposit. Your betting balance is then denominated in fiat currency, protecting you from crypto price volatility while you bet.</p>
                <p>When you withdraw, the site converts your fiat balance back to cryptocurrency at the current exchange rate. This means you might receive more or less crypto than you deposited, depending on price movements. If Bitcoin rises while you're betting, you'll receive less BTC when withdrawing (but it's worth the same in pounds).</p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>Can I Get Bonuses When Betting with Crypto?</h3>
                <p>Most crypto betting sites offer the same welcome bonuses and promotions to crypto depositors as traditional payment users. Some sites even provide crypto-exclusive bonuses with higher percentages or better terms.</p>
                <p>Read bonus terms carefully. Some promotions exclude certain payment methods, though crypto exclusions are becoming rarer. If you're unsure, contact customer support before depositing to confirm your crypto deposit qualifies for advertised bonuses.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>How Do I Know if a Crypto Betting Site is Safe?</h3>
                <p>Check for valid gambling licenses from recognized regulators like the UK Gambling Commission, Malta Gaming Authority, or Curaçao eGaming. Licensed sites undergo regular audits and must maintain player funds in segregated accounts.</p>
                <p>Look for SSL encryption (the padlock icon in your browser's address bar) and verify the site uses proper blockchain verification for transactions. Read user reviews on independent forums—not just testimonials on the site itself—to gauge other bettors' experiences.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>What if I Send Crypto to the Wrong Address?</h3>
                <p>Cryptocurrency transactions are irreversible. If you send crypto to an incorrect address, it's permanently lost unless the recipient voluntarily returns it. This is why double-checking wallet addresses before confirming transactions is crucial.</p>
                <p>Most wallets and betting sites use QR codes to minimize manual address entry errors. Scan QR codes whenever possible rather than copying and pasting addresses. If you must paste an address, verify at minimum the first and last 5-6 characters match what the betting site displayed.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>Do I Need to Pay Taxes on Crypto Betting Winnings?</h3>
                <p>UK residents generally don't pay tax on gambling winnings, regardless of payment method. This applies to crypto winnings the same as traditional currency winnings. However, if you sell cryptocurrency for a profit separate from gambling, that may trigger Capital Gains Tax.</p>
                <p>The distinction matters: if you deposit £100 of Bitcoin, win £50 in bets, and withdraw £150 of Bitcoin, that £50 profit is a tax-free gambling win. But if the Bitcoin itself increases in value between when you bought it and when you sell it for pounds, that capital gain may be taxable.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>Are Crypto Withdrawals Really Faster Than Bank Transfers?</h3>
                <p>Yes, significantly faster. Cryptocurrency withdrawals typically process in minutes to hours, while bank transfers take 3-5 business days. This speed advantage compounds when you withdraw frequently—over a year of weekly withdrawals, crypto saves roughly 150-200 hours of waiting time.</p>
                <p>The speed stems from removing intermediaries. Bank transfers pass through multiple institutions, each adding processing time. Cryptocurrency moves directly from the betting site's wallet to yours with only blockchain confirmation delays—usually 10-30 minutes for Bitcoin, under 5 minutes for Ethereum.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>Which Cryptocurrency is Best for Betting?</h3>
                <p>Bitcoin (BTC) is the most widely accepted and offers the best balance of availability, security, and transaction speed. It's supported by all crypto betting sites and has the most established infrastructure.</p>
                <p>For faster transactions with lower fees, consider Litecoin (LTC) or Bitcoin Cash (BCH). For maximum stability, Tether (USDT) maintains a constant value relative to the pound, eliminating price volatility concerns. Ethereum (ETH) offers smart contract capabilities but has higher network fees during peak times.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

